vision exposure, after controlling for age, body satisfaction, and baseline self-esteem, was significantly related to children's self-esteem. Specifically, television exposure predicted a decrease in self-esteem for White and Black girls and Black boys, and an increase in self-esteem among White boys. The findings are discussed in terms of cultivation theory and social identity theory.}, %0aURL = {http://crx.sagepub.com/content/39/3/338.abstract}, %0aeprint = {http://crx.sagepub.com/content/39/3/338.full.pdf+html}, %0ajournal = {Communication Research} %0a}%0a@]%0a
